reviews.review_text:
Mighty March ‘92 Sometimes I completely underestimate Spring ‘92.

I really enjoyed the Copps Coliseum 3/20/92 show while driving home from a Sabres game a few months ago, and this one is just as smoking while not getting nearly as much attention, so I figured I’d lend a review for those considering a listen who don’t mind spoilers. I popped this one in yesterday during a stormy drive on I-81 up in the North Country, and immediately had my face swiped by the Bruce-era 7-piece band. I’ve had this Miller board on disc for awhile, but had it stashed away for so long that I couldn’t remember the setlist, so I was listening to this one “blind”.

Wondering if I’d picked the right show for the drive, I was quickly blasted away by what I can say without exaggeration is one of the heaviest, most thunderous Jack Straws ever played. Phil and the drummers truly set of the TNT. Jerry follows this up with an Althea that’s good and gritty, with light, atmospheric lead guitar lines soaring above the gravelly, churning instrumental machinery below. What a way to kick of a tour opener! Wang Dang Doodle has moments that probably had any Atlanta blues cats in attendance tapping their feet, and then Jerry strums into an astounding Row Jimmy. ‘92 is a great year for Wake of the Flood songs. They clearly have fun with Stuck Inside of Mobile, but So Many Roads is perhaps the biggest story of the 1st set. The first time it was ever played outside of California - I’d imagine the Omni crowd had no idea what hit them.

To me the next 4 songs have a brief dip in momentum. There’s nothing wrong with them and they’re enjoyable selections, they just lack a bit of the fire that lights up the other tunes. Jerry kicks it back up and takes the whole arena for a run with an invigorating 20-minute Scarlet > Fire. Phil does very well in the transition jam, and the wave of momentum that they create carries them right through the rest of the set. Drums > Space gets pretty technological; it’s more in that alien spaceship dashboard realm than those galactic orbits or milky ways that we sometimes visit in this stage of a show. At first Jerry hints at The Other One, but instead opts for a swaggering Last Time. Next is a great pairing that encapsulates the versatility of this music in a nutshell. During Black Peter, Jerry’s guitar solos tell of a soul resigned to sickness, pain, and a fixation with the sun and fragile mortality. Seconds later, that same guitar is channeling a soul who’s enjoying young love in the springtime. Everyone’s onboard for The Weight, a laid back crowd pleaser which closes out Night 1 in Atlanta.

This one slapped me on the wrist with a ruler and reminded me not to snooze on March ‘92. Lesson learned!
